g with the element <i>grīm</i> ‘mask, helmet’.","Scottish: variant of   Graham  ."]},{"name":"Grahm","meanings":["(1997: 107;2007: 460; 2010: NA)","Scottish (Lanarkshire and northern England): shortened form of   Graham  ."]},{"name":"Grantham","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire and East Yorkshire): habitational name from Grantham in Lincolnshire, of uncertain origin. The final element is Old English <i>hām</i> ‘homestead’; the first may be Old English <i>grand</i> ‘gravel’ or perhaps a personal name <i>Granta</i>, which probably originated as a byname meaning ‘snarler’. See also   Graham  ."]},{"name":"Grahame","meanings":["(1997: 113;2007: 164; 2010: NA)","Scottish: variant of   Graham  . — Note: The population figure published by the US Census Bureau for this surname in the year 2000 is as high as 261, while the figure for 2010 is supposedly lower than 100."]}]},{"name":"Helen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["vernacular form of the name (Greek <i>Hēlēnē</i>) borne in classical legend by a famous beauty, wife of Menelaus, whose seizure by the Trojan prince Paris sparked off the Trojan War. Her name is of uncertain origin; it may be connected with a word meaning ‘ray’ or ‘sunbeam’ compare Greek <i>hēlios</i> ‘sun’. It has sometimes been taken as connected with the Greek word meaning ‘Greek’, <i>Hellēn</i>, but this is doubtful. In the early Christian period the name was borne by the mother of the Emperor Constantine, who is now usually known by the Latin version of her name, <i>Helena</i>. She is credited with having found the True Cross in Jerusalem. She was born in about  248 , probably in Bithynia. However, in medieval England it was believed that she had been born in Britain, which greatly increased the popularity of the name there."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Catherine","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."],"variants":[{"name":"Catheryn","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Katherine","meanings":["Greek: Same as Catherine."]},{"name":"Catharin","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Cathrine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Cathryn","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Cathrin","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Catharine","meanings":["Greek: Pure."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Helen Catherine Graham was born in 1274, in Dunbartonshire, Scotland. She had at least 2 sons with Humphrey Colquhoun 4th Colquhoun of Ilk. She died in 1310, in her hometown, at the age of 36."},"et":{"1274–1310":"1274–1310","1280–1330":"1280–1330","1310–1390":"1310–1390","1328–1391":"1328–1391","1310":"1310","1330":"1330","1274":"1274","1391":"1391","1390":"1390","1280":"1280","1328":"1328","Dunbartonshire, Scotland":"Dunbartonshire, Scotland","Dunbartonshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Dunbartonshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1274–1310":"1274–1310","1280–1330":"1280–1330","1310–1390":"1310–1390","1328–1391":"1328–1391","1310":"1310","1330":"1330","1274":"1274","1391":"1391","1390":"1390","1280":"1280","1328":"1328","Dunbartonshire, Scotland":"Dunbartonshire, Scotland","Dunbartonshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Dunbartonshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1274–1310":"1274–1310","1280–1330":"1280–1330","1310–1390":"1310–1390","1328–1391":"1328–1391","1310":"1310","1330":"1330","1274":"1274","1391":"1391","1390":"1390","1280":"1280","1328":"1328","Dunbartonshire, Scotland":"Dunbartonshire, Écosse","Dunbartonshire, Scotland, United Kin